---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import d from '../data/site_data.json';
import { pct, count, cellType } from '../lib/fmt.js';

const title = 'Challenge & data — Dual-marker discovery';
const description =
  'The biological problem, the single-cell atlases behind the scan, and how a candidate marker pair is actually scored.';

const tumor = d.datasets.find((x) => x.dataset.includes('tumor'));
const healthy = d.datasets.find((x) => x.dataset.includes('tabula'));
---
<Base title={title} description={description} page="challenge">
  <section class="hero" style="padding-bottom:0.6rem">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">The setup</p>
      <h1>The challenge and the data</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Find two surface markers that together separate prostate cancer from every healthy human cell
        type, and make the claim checkable by requiring the method to rediscover a pair we already know
        the answer to.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <h2>The biology</h2>
      <p>
        Antigen-directed therapy in solid tumors runs into a wall that is not a targeting failure. It is
        a targeting success against the wrong cell. A single tumor antigen is rarely absent from every
        healthy tissue, so CAR-T, T-cell engagers, and antibody-drug conjugates that key on one antigen
        carry real on-target, off-tumor risk. PSMA is a good prostate antigen and it is also in your
        duodenum.
      </p>
      <p>
        Requiring two conditions before a cell is engaged can recover the specificity that one antigen
        cannot provide. Prostate is the natural test bed, because it has a combinatorial answer already
        in hand: PSMA and PSCA are a preclinically validated split-signal AND-gate CAR. A scan that
        cannot find that pair has not earned the right to nominate a new one.
      </p>

      <h2>The question</h2>
      <div class="callout">
        <p>
          Across a curated panel of {d.study.n_panel_genes_scanned} cell-surface markers, which pairs
          separate malignant prostate cells from every healthy human cell type, under AND logic or NOT
          logic, when scored per patient rather than on pooled cells? And does the scan recover
          PSMA-PSCA before it proposes anything new?
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2>The data</h2>
      <div class="tw">
        <table class="fig">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Source</th>
              <th class="num">Cells</th>
              <th class="num">Donors</th>
              <th>What it contributes</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><b>Localised prostate tumor cohort</b><br /><span class="ct">hormone therapy naive adenocarcinoma</span></td>
              <td class="num">{count(tumor?.n_cells)}</td>
              <td class="num">{tumor?.n_donors}</td>
              <td class="ct">
                {count(d.study.n_malignant_cells)} malignant cells after doublet removal, plus
                {' '}{count(d.study.n_benign_cells)} adjacent-benign prostate cells kept as a matched
                same-patient control. Malignant identity is the authors' copy-number and signature call.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><b>Tabula Sapiens 2.0</b><br /><span class="ct">via CELLxGENE Census, release 2025-01-30</span></td>
              <td class="num">{count(d.study.n_healthy_cells)}</td>
              <td class="num">—</td>
              <td class="ct">
                The safety denominator. {d.study.n_healthy_celltypes} cell types across
                {' '}{d.study.n_healthy_tissues} tissue labels, forming {d.study.n_healthy_populations}
                {' '}donor-replicated tissue-by-cell-type populations. Restricted to the 10x 3' v3 assay to
                match the tumor chemistry, because a raw-count positivity threshold is not comparable
                across assays.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><b>Human Protein Atlas</b></td>
              <td class="num">—</td>
              <td class="num">—</td>
              <td class="ct">
                Subcellular localization and normal-tissue RNA, used to qualify surface accessibility and
                cross-check the normal-tissue liabilities found in the single-cell data.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>How a pair is scored</h2>
      <ol class="steps">
        <li>
          <b>Positivity is per cell, not per sample.</b> A cell counts as positive for a marker at a raw
          count of at least {d.study.k_threshold}. The threshold is swept for sensitivity rather than
          asserted. Nothing is averaged into a pseudo-bulk value first.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Coverage is computed within each patient, never pooled.</b> For markers A and B, AND
          coverage is the fraction of that patient's malignant cells positive for both. The
          {' '}{d.study.n_patients_scored} per-patient scores are then summarized by their median and,
          more importantly, their lower decile: the floor, the worst-served patient. A donor with
          thousands of cells cannot carry a pair on its own.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Every pair is held against three references.</b> Malignant coverage; the matched benign
          prostate from the same cohort, so a pair expressed across the whole gland is penalised rather
          than rewarded; and the worst-case co-positive fraction across the healthy atlas.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>The healthy side is made donor-robust.</b> Within each tissue-by-cell-type population the
          fraction is computed per donor and summarized by the median across donors, keeping only
          populations with at least two donors. One unusual donor, or a population of nine cells, cannot
          set a worst case. Every liability we report carries its supporting donor and cell counts.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Confounded pairs are excluded, not quietly ranked.</b> The cohort's malignant label is built
          partly from expression signatures containing HPN and EPCAM. Any pair containing those genes is
          scoring against a label it helped define, so it is flagged, held off the frontier, and never
          nominated.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Ranking is a Pareto frontier, not a single score.</b> Coverage floor against worst
          extra-prostatic liability. No weighting of one against the other is invented, because the
          clinically acceptable trade is not ours to assert. Only surface-accessible markers can be
          nominated.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Why liabilities exclude the prostate</h2>
      <p>
        Both statistics are computed and both are kept in the tables. The figures lead with the
        extra-prostatic one, because normal prostate expression may be clinically tolerable in selected
        advanced-disease contexts where the gland is already being treated, whereas every other organ is
        dose-limiting. The stricter all-organ number is one column away and is not hidden.
      </p>

      <h2>What would falsify this</h2>
      <p>
        If the scan had failed to recover PSMA-PSCA, the ranking behind it would carry no weight, and the
        honest report would have been that the method does not work. The control is not decoration. It is
        the reason the rest of the numbers are worth reading. The
        {' '}<a href="/report">limitations section</a> lists what the control does not buy us, starting
        with the fact that co-detected transcript is not co-expressed protein.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
